'''Omiashi Shrine''' (おみあしじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Asuka|Q752397|WD=Q752397|1=Asuka, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Takaichi District|Q1117901|WD=Q1117901|1=Takaichi District, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, formerly ranked as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. It stands on the site of '''{{ill|lt=Hinokuma-dera|Q11544640|WD=Q11544640|1=Hinokuma-dera}}'''.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* Two deities, husband and wife, of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Achi no Omi|1=UNKNOWN}} - ancestral deities of the {{ill|lt=Yamato-no-Aya clan|Q10870550|WD=Q10870550|1=Yamatonoaya clan}}.

=== History ===
This area is said to have been the residence site of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Achi no Omi|1=UNKNOWN}}, who came to Japan in the reign of the 15th emperor, {{ill|lt=Emperor Ojin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}. In the late {{ill|lt=7th century|Q8089|WD=Q8089|1=7th century}}, {{ill|lt=Hinokuma-dera|Q11544640|WD=Q11544640|1=Hinokuma-dera}} was built as the {{ill|lt=ujidera|Q11547815|WD=Q11547815|1=Clan temple}} of the {{ill|lt=Yamato-no-Aya clan|Q10870550|WD=Q10870550|1=Yamatonoaya clan}}.

Later, west of the present site across the road, this shrine was founded as the {{ill|lt=ujigami|Q767655|WD=Q767655|1=Ujigami}} of the Yamato-no-Aya clan, with Achi no Omi and his wife as {{ill|lt=enshrined deities|Q11591100|WD=Q11591100|1=Saijin}}{{Sfn|日本の神社研究会|2018|page=142}}, and as the guardian shrine of Hinokuma-dera.

By the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|WD=Q236205|1=Kamakura period}}, Hinokuma-dera was called Doko-ji, and in the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}} this shrine was called Goryo Myojin.

When {{ill|lt=Motoori Norinaga|Q384647|WD=Q384647|1=Motoori Norinaga}} visited in {{ill|lt=1772|Q7690|WD=Q7690|1=1772}} ({{ill|lt=Meiwa|Q1146161|WD=Q1146161|1=Meiwa}} 9), only a temporary hut remained at Hinokuma-dera and old roof tiles were scattered in the precincts; Hinokuma-dera was later abolished.

In {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|WD=Q2048|1=1907}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 40), the main hall was relocated to the former site of Hinokuma-dera.

It is also said that {{ill|lt=Emperor Senka|Q329728|WD=Q329728|1=Emperor Senka}}'s {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hinokuma Iorino-no-Miya|1=UNKNOWN}} stood in this area, though this is uncertain.

=== Precincts ===
* Main hall
* Worship hall
* Site of Hinokuma-dera lecture hall - foundation stones remain.
* Eleven-tier stone pagoda ({{ill|lt=Important Cultural Property|Q1188622|WD=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}}) - believed originally to have been a thirteen-tier pagoda made in the late {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}. The upper part is damaged, so it is now eleven tiers. It stands on the former pagoda platform of Hinokuma-dera.
* Hinokuma-dera pagoda site - platform remains. The nearby central foundation stone is a replica.
* Shrine office

